\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439|first=\u0418\u043b\u044c\u044f|date=2013-07-16|website=|publisher=[[European Radio for Belarus]]|language=ru|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408104428/http://euroradio.fm/ru/kak-na-basovishche-rychal-tabolich-krama-otpravila-instrumenty-v-peterburg|archivedate=2016-04-08|accessdate=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.svaboda.org/a/30051641.html|title=\u041d\u0435\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043a\u0456 \u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u045e \u043f\u0440\u0430 \"\u0411\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0448\u0447\u0430\", \u044f\u043a\u0456\u0445 \u043d\u044f \u0441\u043a\u0430\u0436\u0430 \u043d\u0456\u0445\u0442\u043e|last=\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0456\u043c\u044e\u043a|first=\u042f\u043d|date=2019-07-13|website=|publisher=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]|language=be|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306191202/https://www.svaboda.org/a/30051641.html|archivedate=2020-03-06|accessdate=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\nThe festival takes place during two July days in the Borak forest near [[Gmina of Gr\u00f3dek]], [[Poland]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jul/20/belarus-opposition-music-festival-poland-basowiszcza |title='Here we breathe freedom': Basowiszcza festival amplifies Belarus opposition |agency=AFP |date=2015-07-20|newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222174618/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jul/20/belarus-opposition-music-festival-poland-basowiszcza |archivedate=2020-02-22 |access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> The important part of the festival is the music contest, in which young bands compete for prizes - usually money and rights to record their album for free.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://music.fromby.net/news/bas_nasha.html|title=\"\u0411\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0448\u0447\u0430-2004\": \u043d\u0430\u0448\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0447\u0430|last=\u041c\u0456\u043d\u0447\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043a|first=\u0410\u043b\u044f\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0439|year=2004|publisher=[[Tuzin.fm]]|language=be|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040803011250/http://music.fromby.net/news/bas_nasha.html|archivedate=2004-08-03|accessdate=2019-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://generation.by/news6134.html|title=\u0423 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441\u0435 \u0411\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0448\u0447\u0430 \u0441\u0451\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0441\u043f\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u0456\u0447\u0430\u044e\u0446\u044c 28 \u0433\u0443\u0440\u0442\u043e\u045e|last=\u041a\u0430\u043d\u0430\u043f\u043a\u0456\u043d|first=\u042f\u0433\u043e\u0440|date=2013-06-04|publisher=Generation.by|language=be|trans-title=28 bands are competing in this year's Basovi\u0161\u010da competition|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031234148/http://generation.by/news6134.html|archive-date=2013-10-31|url-status=live|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u041a\u0430\u0440\u043f\u044e\u043a|first=\u0406\u043b\u043e\u043d\u0430|date=2010-07-25|title=\u0422\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u0456 \u201e\u0437\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0447\u043a\u0456\u201d \u043d\u0430 \u201e\u0411\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0448\u0447\u044b-2010\u201d \u043d\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u0441\u0432\u044f\u0446\u0456\u043b\u0456\u0441\u044f|url=http://niva.bialystok.pl/issue/2010/30/30_2010.pdf|url-status=live|journal=[[Niva (newspaper)|Niva]]|language=be|volume=|issue=30|pages=3|issn=0546-1960|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318180545/http://niva.bialystok.pl/issue/2010/30/30_2010.pdf|archivedate=2020-03-18|accessdate=2020-03-18|via=}}</ref> Well-known stars of [[Belarus]]ian, [[Rock music in Ukraine|Ukrainian]] and Polish rock-scene usually perform there too.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nn.by/?c=ar&i=113003&lang=ru|title=\u0417\u0432\u0435\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043c\u0438 \"\u0411\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0449\u0430\" \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438 \"Dzieciuki\": \u0444\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0436|last=\u0420\u0443\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|first=\u041e\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0430|date=2013-07-23|website=|publisher=[[\u041d\u0430\u0448\u0430 \u041d\u0456\u0432\u0430]]|language=ru|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221192936/https://nn.by/?c=ar&i=113003&lang=ru|archivedate=2020-02-21|accessdate=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://euroradio.fm/ru/basovishcha-kak-novyy-god-mozhet-byt-raznym-no-vse-ravno-ego-otmechaesh|title=\"\u0411\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0448\u0447\u0430\" \u2014 \u043a\u0430\u043a \u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0433\u043e\u0434: \u043c\u043e\u0436\u0435\u0442 \u0431\u044b\u0442\u044c \u0440\u0430\u0437\u043d\u044b\u043c, \u043d\u043e \u0432\u0441\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0432\u043d\u043e \u0435\u0433\u043e \u043e\u0442\u043c\u0435\u0447\u0430\u0435\u0448\u044c|last=\u041a\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430|first=\u041c\u0430\u0448\u0430|date=2014-07-22|website=|publisher=[[European Radio for Belarus]]|language=ru|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317190114/https://euroradio.fm/ru/basovishcha-kak-novyy-god-mozhet-byt-raznym-no-vse-ravno-ego-otmechaesh|archivedate=2020-03-17|accessdate=2020-03-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://euroradio.fm/basovishcha-geta-yak-novy-god-mozha-byc-roznym-ale-ty-yago-adznachaesh|title=\"\u0411\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0448\u0447\u0430\" \u2014 \u0433\u044d\u0442\u0430 \u044f\u043a \u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b \u0433\u043e\u0434: \u043c\u043e\u0436\u0430 \u0431\u044b\u0446\u044c \u0440\u043e\u0437\u043d\u044b\u043c, \u0430\u043b\u0435 \u0442\u044b \u044f\u0433\u043e \u0430\u0434\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u0435\u0448|last=\u041a\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0456\u043a\u0430\u0432\u0430|first=\u041c\u0430\u0448\u0430|date=2014-07-22|website=|publisher=[[European Radio for Belarus]]|language=be|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317190715/https://euroradio.fm/basovishcha-geta-yak-novy-god-mozha-byc-roznym-ale-ty-yago-adznachaesh|archivedate=2020-03-17|accessdate=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===2006===\n17th Basovi\u0161\u010da was held on July 22\u201323, 2006. Contest was on second day. It was the first time when a band from [[Lithuania]], [[IR (band)|IR]], took part in it.\n\n====Contest results====\n'''Winners''':<ref>{{cite news \n |url=http://music.fromby.net/articles.php?id=291 \n |title=\u0412\u044b\u043d\u0456\u043a\u0456 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441\u0443 \"\u0411\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0448\u0447\u0430-2006\" (''Results of Basovi\u0161\u010da-2006 contest'') \n |publisher=[[Tuzin.fm]] \n |date=2006-07-23 \n |accessdate=2006-07-30 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070310130202/http://music.fromby.net/articles.php?id=291 \n |archivedate=2007-03-10 \n }}</ref>\n*[[Parason]] - 40 hours of recording in Apollo Studio, and money (1800 zl)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://euroradio.fm/kudy-znikayuc-peramozhcy-basovishcha|title=\u041a\u0443\u0434\u044b \u0437\u043d\u0456\u043a\u0430\u044e\u0446\u044c \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0436\u0446\u044b \"\u0411\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0448\u0447\u0430\"?|last=\u0428\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0446|first=\u041c\u0456\u0440\u0430|date=2013-07-15|website=|publisher=[[European Radio for Belarus]]|language=be|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718092636/http://euroradio.fm/kudy-znikayuc-peramozhcy-basovishcha|archivedate=2013-07-18|accessdate=2020-01-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://euroradio.fm/ru/kuda-ischezayut-pobediteli-basovishcha|title=\u041a\u0443\u0434\u0430 \u0438\u0441\u0447\u0435\u0437\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u043f\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438 \"\u0411\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0449\u0430\"?|last=\u0428\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0446|first=\u041c\u0438\u0440\u0430|date=2013-07-15|website=|publisher=[[European Radio for Belarus]]|language=ru|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130721030031/http://euroradio.fm/ru/kuda-ischezayut-pobediteli-basovishcha|archivedate=2013-07-21|accessdate=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n*[[S.D.M. (band)|S.D.M.]] - 25 hours of recording in Studio Rembrandt Radio Bialystok, and money (1200 zl)\n*[[Nevma]] - 1360 zl\n* [[Ludzi \u015bviatla]] - 1000 zl\n*[[Vodar su\u015bviet]] - electric guitar\n\n''Other participants'': [[Band A]], [[Krok (band)|Krok]], [[RoStra]], [[Termin X]], [[Mozart (band)|Mozart]]\n\n====Line up====\n''Friday, July 21'': [[IR (band)|IR]] ([[Lithuania|LT]]), [[5set5]] ([[Poland|PL]]), [[Rima (band)|Rima]] (PL), [[Orchestra Arturo Piazza]] ([[Italy|ITA]]), Ambasadar KROU/[[\u010cyrvonym pa Bie\u0142ym|\u010cpB]] ([[Belarus|BY]]), [[Siddhartha (band)|Siddhartha]] (PL), [[Troitsa]] (BY), [[Zero-85]] (PL), [[Neuro Dubel]] (BY)\n\n''Saturday, July 22'': [[Imprudence]] (BY), [[\u0179miaja]] (BY), [[Indiga (band)|Indiga]] (BY), [[Tav.Mauzer]] (BY), [[Krama (band)|Krama]] (BY), [[Sjel]] (PL), [[B:N:|:B:N:]] (BY), [[Red Emprez]] (PL), [[Drum Ecstasy]] (BY), [[IQ48]] (BY), [[N.R.M.]] (BY)\n\n== Bans ==\nIn 2006, the organizers faced a ban on the concerts of \u201cAdbory\u0161\u010da\u201d (qualifying rounds for \u201cBasovi\u0161\u010da-2006\u201d) in [[Minsk]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mpby.ru/news-671.htm|title=\"\u0411\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0448\u0447\u0430\" - \u0456\u0434\u044d\u0430\u043b\u044f\u0433\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0431\u044f\u0441\u044c\u043f\u0435\u0447\u043d\u0430\u0435 \u043c\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043f\u0440\u044b\u0435\u043c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430|last=\u0411\u0443\u0434\u043a\u0456\u043d|first=\u0421\u044f\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0439|last2=\u041c\u0456\u043d\u0447\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043a|first2=\u0410\u043b\u044f\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0439|date=2006-06-23|publisher=mpby.ru|work=[[Tuzin.fm]]|language=be|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117144443/http://mpby.ru/news-671.htm|archivedate=2019-11-17|accessdate=2019-11-17}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nIn 2008 Rock-Princess Kasia Kamockaja as a columnist over at [[naviny.by]] made such a takeaway on the festival, ''\u201c\u201eBasovi\u0161\u010da\u201c was conceived not as a festival of Belarusian music in exile, but as a celebration of local [[Bia\u0142ystok]] Belarusians.\u201d''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://naviny.by/rubrics/opinion/2008/08/17/ic_articles_410_158521|title=\u041a\u0430\u0441\u044f \u041a\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0446\u043a\u0430\u044f. \u0428\u041e\u0423-\u0411\u0406\u0417. \u0421\u0430\u043b\u0456\u0434\u0430\u0440\u043d\u044b \u0437 \u0440\u043e\u043a-\u043d-\u0440\u043e\u043b\u0430\u043c?|last=\u041a\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0446\u043a\u0430\u044f|first=\u041a\u0430\u0441\u044f|date=2008-08-17|authorlink=Kasia Kamockaja|publisher=[[naviny.by]]|language=be|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330041249/http://naviny.by/rubrics/opinion/2008/08/17/ic_articles_410_158521/|archivedate=2015-03-30|accessdate=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\nOn the pages of [[BelGazeta]], Tat'''\u2019'''yana Zamirovskaya wrote in 2007 that the festival ''\u201cis the only and oldest music competition in which young Belarusian rock bands can prove themselves and get a very significant prize.\u201d''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u0417\u0430\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f|first=\u0422\u0430\u0442\u044c\u044f\u043d\u0430|date=2007-06-18|title=\u0424\u0430\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \"\u0415\u0432\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f\"|url=http://www.belgazeta.by/ru/2007_06_18/radosti_zhizni/14242/|url-status=live|journal=[[BelGazeta]]|language=ru|volume=24|issue=594|pages=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215074226/http://www.belgazeta.by/ru/2007_06_18/radosti_zhizni/14242/|archivedate=2020-02-15|accessdate=2020-02-15|via=}}</ref> \n\nIn the retrospect of 2010\u20132019 in 2019, Lesha Gorbash from [[34mag]] called the festival ''\u201ca [[Mecca]] for [[Rock music in Belarus|Belarusian rock music]].\u201d''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://34mag.net/piarshak/post/belmusic-timeline|title=\u0412\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043c\u043d\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0432\u0441\u0435: \u0442\u0430\u0439\u043c\u043b\u0430\u0439\u043d \u0431\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0438 2010\u20132019|last=\u0413\u043e\u0440\u0431\u0430\u0448|first=\u041b\u0435\u0448\u0430|last2=\u041a\u0430\u0448\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432|first2=\u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d|date=2019-12-26|website=|last3=palasatka|publisher=[[34mag]]|language=ru|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230064444/https://34mag.net/piarshak/post/belmusic-timeline|archivedate=2019-12-30|accessdate=2019-12-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Basowiszcza}}\n* {{in lang|be|pl}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20060219141945/http://www.basowiszcza.org/ Basovi\u0161\u010da \u2014 the official web-site]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Basovisca}}\n[[Category:Belarusian music]]\n[[Category:Censorship in Belarus]]\n\n\n{{Belarus-stub}}\n{{music-festival-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Greyjoy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCriticism", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basovi%C5%A1%C4%8Da"}
{"title_page": "Industrial Canada", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Industrial Canada\n| image          = Screen shot Industrial Canada.png\n| caption        = Title frame\n| director       ={{Interlanguage link multi|Guy L. Cot\u00e9|fr}}\n| producer       ={{plainlist|\n* Guy L. Cot\u00e9\n* Nicholas Balla (Executive producer)\n}}\n| writer         ={{plainlist|\n* Guy L. Cot\u00e9\n* {{Interlanguage link multi|Gilbert Choquette|fr}}\n}}\n| narrator       =Budd Knapp\n| starring       =\n| music          =\n| cinematography =Reginald Morris\n| editing        =Guy L. Cot\u00e9\n| studio         = [[National Film Board of Canada]]\n| distributor    = {{plainlist|\n* [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]\n* National Film Board of Canada\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|1958}} (broadcast date)\n| runtime        = 18 minutes, 27 seconds\n| country        = Canada\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n\n'''''Industrial Canada''''' is a 1958 18-minute Canadian [[short subject|short]] [[National Film Board of Canada]] (NFB) [[documentary film]] produced, directed and edited by Guy L. Cot\u00e9 for the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] (CBC) television series,  as part of the postwar ''[[Canada Carries On]]'' series. ''Industrial Canada'' documents the industrial development of Canada during the mid-1950s. The film's [[Canadian French|French]] version title is ''Le Canada industriel''.<ref name=\"CFE\">Morris, Peter. [http://www.filmreferencelibrary.ca/index.asp?layid=44&csid1=615&navid=66 \"Film Reference Library: Canada Carries On.\"]{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''Canadian Film Encyclopedia''. Retrieved: February 28, 2016.</ref> {{TOC limit|limit=2}}\n\n== Synopsis ==\nIn the short span of 50 years, Canada has transformed from a primarily agricultural economy to a nation increasingly reliant on an industrial base. Throughout the 20th Century, more than half of the population was involved in agrarian activities and rural life, with numerous small towns and villages spread across the country.\n\nThe traditional way of life based on back-breaking toil and skills passed on through the generations to provide for food and necessities was changing. An increased demand for commodities resulted in the adoption of mechanization, the assembly line and mass production. As industries began to compete with agriculture, more of a reliance on factories and cities began to change the Canadian landscape.\n\nCanada is rich in natural resources with an abundance of raw materials necessary for industrial development. Minerals such as asbestos, iron, uranium, nickel, copper, gold and zinc were available for both export and domestic use. With the availability of vast reservoirs of water to create [[Hydroelectricity|hydro-electric power]] and the \"black gold\" of coal mines, basic metals can be produced, such as aluminum.\n\nWhen war came to Canada in the 1940s, massive engineering and manufacturing centres were created to produce the weapons of war from detonator caps to four-engined bombers. Industrial production was greatly increased with the addition of many new mines and smelters in the most northerly regions of the Canadian Shield, with new communities built around them.\n\nBuilding on the industrial progress of wartime, in a postwar world, Canadian factories and manufacturing plants were able to pivot to new products and industries, such as the design of commercial and military aircraft, creating atomic power plants and introducing \"electronic\" brains to business applications. New discoveries of oil in the Canadian prairies led to the development of a [[petrochemical industry]]. Technological advances led to an industrial sector able to handle all aspects of production of many \"made in Canada\" products.\n\nAlthough production and export of commodities such as pulp and paper are still essential to a strong economy, Canadian industry is able to diversify to produce a multitude of domestic items such as pots and pans, washing machines, television sets and bicycles. Far from the industrial centres, new communities have grown up in the suburbs. With industrial development, life in Canada continues to change with a steadily growing prosperity and workers benefitting with more security, shorter hours and a safer, more pleasant workplace.\n\n==Production==\n''Industrial Canada'' was  part of the NFB's ''Canada Carries On'' series of documentary short films for [[CBC Television]]. Most postwar programs dealt with contemporary issues in Canada.<ref>Lerner 1997, p. 196.</ref> The film was a [[compilation documentary]] edited to provide a coherent story, that relied heavily on newsreel material in order to provide the background to the dialogue.<ref>Gittings 2001, p. 80.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Excerpts from other NFB documentaries such as ''[[Target - Berlin]]'' and ''[[Screaming Jets (film)|Screaming Jets]]'' were featured.|group=Note}}  Additional footage was shot for the film by an NFB team of cinematographer Reginald Morris and sound engineer George Croll. Final sound editing in the studio was undertaken by Stuart Baker and Donald Douglas.\n\n==Reception==\n''Industrial Canada'' was primarily [[made-for-television]] on the CBC, and after broadcast, the film was made available on 16&nbsp;mm to schools, libraries and other interested parties. The film was also made available to film libraries operated by university and provincial authorities.<ref name=\"Ohayon\">Ohayon, Albert. [http://blog.nfb.ca/2009/07/13/propaganda-cinema/ \"Propaganda cinema at the NFB\".] ''National Film Board of Canada'', July 13, 2009. Retrieved: February 28, 2016.</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* Gittings, Chris. ''Canadian National Cinema: Ideology, Difference and Representation''. London: Routledge, 2001. {{ISBN|978-0-4151-4282-3}}.\n* Lerner, Loren. ''Canadian Film and Video: A Bibliography and Guide to the Literature''. Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1997. {{ISBN|978-0-8020-2988-1}}.\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://onf-nfb.gc.ca/en/our-collection/?idfilm=14469 ''Industrial Canada''  at NFB Collections website]\n* {{IMDb title|0226829|Industrial Canada}}\n\n[[Category:1958 films]]\n[[Category:Canadian short documentary films]]\n[[Category:Canadian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:National Film Board of Canada documentaries]]\n[[Category:1950s documentary films]]\n[[Category:Industrial history of Canada]]\n[[Category:Canada Carries On]]\n[[Category:Quebec films]]\n[[Category:National Film Board of Canada short films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Industrial Canada\n| image          = Screen shot Industrial Canada.png\n| caption        = Title frame\n| director       ={{Interlanguage link multi|Guy L. Cot\u00e9|fr}}\n| producer       ={{plainlist|\n* Guy L. Cot\u00e9\n* Nicholas Balla (Executive producer)\n}}\n| writer         ={{plainlist|\n* Guy L. Cot\u00e9\n* {{Interlanguage link multi|Gilbert Choquette|fr}}\n}}\n| narrator       =Budd Knapp\n| starring       =\n| music          =\n| cinematography =Reginald Morris\n| editing        =Guy L. Cot\u00e9\n| studio         = [[National Film Board of Canada]]\n| distributor    = {{plainlist|\n* [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]\n* National Film Board of Canada\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|1958}} (broadcast date)\n| runtime        = 18 minutes, 27 seconds\n| country        = Canada\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n\n'''''Industrial Canada''''' is a 1958 18-minute Canadian [[short subject|short]] [[National Film Board of Canada]] (NFB) [[documentary film]] produced, directed and edited by Guy L. Cot\u00e9 for the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] (CBC) television series,  as part of the postwar ''[[Canada Carries On]]'' series. ''Industrial Canada'' documents the industrial development of Canada during the mid-1950s. The film's [[Canadian French|French]] version title is ''Le Canada industriel''.<ref name=\"CFE\">Morris, Peter. [http://www.filmreferencelibrary.ca/index.asp?layid=44&csid1=615&navid=66 \"Film Reference Library: Canada Carries On.\"]{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''Canadian Film Encyclopedia''. Retrieved: February 28, 2016.</ref> {{TOC limit|limit=2}}\n\n== Synopsis ==\nIn the short span of 50 years, Canada has transformed from a primarily agricultural economy to a nation increasingly reliant on an industrial base. Throughout the 20th Century, more than half of the population was involved in agrarian activities and rural life, with numerous small towns and villages spread across the country.\n\nThe traditional way of life based on back-breaking toil and skills passed on through the generations to provide for food and necessities was changing. An increased demand for commodities resulted in the adoption of mechanization, the assembly line and mass production. As industries began to compete with agriculture, more of a reliance on factories and cities began to change the Canadian landscape.\n\nCanada is rich in natural resources with an abundance of raw materials necessary for industrial development. Minerals such as asbestos, iron, uranium, nickel, copper, gold and zinc were available for both export and domestic use. With the availability of vast reservoirs of water to create [[Hydroelectricity|hydro-electric power]] and the \"black gold\" of coal mines, basic metals can be produced, such as aluminum.\n\nWhen war came to Canada in the 1940s, massive engineering and manufacturing centres were created to produce the weapons of war from detonator caps to four-engined bombers. Industrial production was greatly increased with the addition of many new mines and smelters in the most northerly regions of the Canadian Shield, with new communities built around them.\n\nBuilding on the industrial progress of wartime, in a postwar world, Canadian factories and manufacturing plants were able to pivot to new products and industries, such as the design of commercial and military aircraft, creating atomic power plants and introducing \"electronic\" brains to business applications. New discoveries of oil in the Canadian prairies led to the development of a [[petrochemical industry]]. Technological advances led to an industrial sector able to handle all aspects of production of many \"made in Canada\" products.\n\nAlthough production and export of commodities such as pulp and paper are still essential to a strong economy, Canadian industry is able to diversify to produce a multitude of domestic items such as pots and pans, washing machines, television sets and bicycles. Far from the industrial centres, new communities have grown up in the suburbs. With industrial development, life in Canada continues to change with a steadily growing prosperity and workers benefitting with more security, shorter hours and a safer, more pleasant workplace.\n\n==Production==\n''Industrial Canada'' was  part of the NFB's ''Canada Carries On'' series of documentary short films for [[CBC Television]]. Most postwar programs dealt with contemporary issues in Canada.<ref>Lerner 1997, p. 196.</ref> The film was a [[compilation documentary]] edited to provide a coherent story, that relied heavily on newsreel material in order to provide the background to the dialogue.<ref>Gittings 2001, p. 80.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Excerpts from other NFB documentaries such as ''[[Target - Berlin]]'' and ''[[Screaming Jets (film)|Screaming Jets]]'' were featured.|group=Note}}  Additional footage was shot for the film by an NFB team of cinematographer Reginald Morris and sound engineer George Croll. Final sound editing in the studio was undertaken by Stuart Baker and Donald Douglas.\n\n==Reception==\n''Industrial Canada'' was primarily [[made-for-television]] on the CBC, and after broadcast, the film was made available on 16&nbsp;mm to schools, libraries and other interested parties. The film was also made available to film libraries operated by university and provincial authorities.<ref name=\"Ohayon\">Ohayon, Albert. [http://blog.nfb.ca/2009/07/13/propaganda-cinema/ \"Propaganda cinema at the NFB\".] ''National Film Board of Canada'', July 13, 2009. Retrieved: February 28, 2016.</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* Gittings, Chris. ''Canadian National Cinema: Ideology, Difference and Representation''. London: Routledge, 2001. {{ISBN|978-0-4151-4282-3}}.\n* Lerner, Loren. ''Canadian Film and Video: A Bibliography and Guide to the Literature''. Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1997. {{ISBN|978-0-8020-2988-1}}.\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://onf-nfb.gc.ca/en/our-collection/?idfilm=14469 ''Industrial Canada''  at NFB Collections website]\n* {{IMDb title|0226829|Industrial Canada}}\n\n[[Category:1958 films]]\n[[Category:Canadian short films]]\n[[Category:Canadian short documentary films]]\n[[Category:Canadian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:National Film Board of Canada documentaries]]\n[[Category:1950s documentary films]]\n[[Category:Industrial history of Canada]]\n[[Category:Canada Carries On]]\n[[Category:Quebec films]]\n[[Category:National Film Board of Canada short films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:duplicate categorization; already in subcat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Industrial_Canada"}
{"title_page": "If You Love This Planet", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = If You Love This Planet\n| image          = If You Love This Planet (film).jpg\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Terre Nash]]\n| producer       = [[Edward Le Lorrain]]\n| writer         =\n| narrator       =\n| starring       =\n| music          = [[Karl du Plessis]]\n| cinematography = [[Andr\u00e9-Luc Dupont]]<br />[[Susan Trow]]<br />[[Don Virgo]]\n| editing        =\n| distributor    = [[National Film Board of Canada]] (NFB)\n| released       = 1982\n| runtime        = 26 minutes\n| country        = Canada\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| preceded_by    =\n| followed_by    =\n}}\n'''''If You Love This Planet''''' is a 1982 short [[documentary film]] recording a lecture given to [[State University of New York at Plattsburgh|SUNY Plattsburgh]] students by physician and [[anti-nuclear]] activist Dr. [[Helen Caldicott]] about the dangers posed by [[nuclear weapon]]s.  The movie was directed by [[Terre Nash]] and produced by [[Edward Le Lorrain]] for [[National Film Board of Canada#Studio D|Studio D, the women's studio of the National Film Board of Canada]]. Studio D head [[Kathleen Shannon]] was executive producer.<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=Canada|first=National Film Board of|title=If You Love This Planet|url=https://www.nfb.ca/film/if_you_love_this_planet/|language=en|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref>\n\nReleased during the term of the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan administration]] and at the height<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.history.com/topics/cold-war/cold-war-history|title=Cold War History|last=Editors|first=History com|website=HISTORY|language=en|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref> of [[Cold War]] nuclear tensions between the United States and [[Soviet Union]], ''If You Love This Planet'' was officially designated as \"foreign political propaganda\" by the [[United States Department of Justice]] and temporarily banned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://explore.lib.virginia.edu/exhibits/show/censored/walkthrough/film2|title=CENSORED: Wielding the Red Pen (Online Exhibit)|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=23 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Verbinski|first=Jane|title=If You Love This Planet Gov't censors pick best short|journal=Jump Cut|date=April 1983|issue=28|page=64|url=http://www.ejumpcut.org/archive/onlinessays/JC28folder/CensorShort.html|accessdate=23 November 2013}}</ref>  The subsequent uproar over that action gave the film a [[Streisand Effect|publicity boost]], and it later won the 1982 [[Academy Award for Best Documentary (Short Subject)]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/300477/If-You-Love-This-Planet/details |title=If You Love This Planet |accessdate=2008-12-01|work=The New York Times}}</ref> [[CBC Television]] initially refused to air the film, claiming it was biased.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nelson|first=Joyce|date=1983|title=Film Reviews/Terri Nash's \"If You Love This Planet\"|url=http://cinemacanada.athabascau.ca/index.php/cinema/article/view/1715|journal=Cinema Canada|language=en|volume=0|issue=0|issn=1918-879X}}</ref> It debuted in the [[United Kingdom]] when it was screened by the London Socialist Film Co-op.<ref>Matthew Hays, [http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/1997/032097/film1.html \"Montreal Oscar Stories: Two of the city's award-winners reminisce\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020823090711/http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/1997/032097/film1.html |date=2002-08-23 }} ''Montreal Mirror'', March 21, 1997.  Accessed 2008.12.18.</ref>\n\n== Significance ==\nThe film goes into depth describing in easy-to-understand language the scientific and medical consequences of [[ozone depletion]], the [[greenhouse effect]], [[deforestation]], toxic chemical pollution, [[species extinction]], [[food contamination]], [[Nuclear Waste|nuclear waste]], and the constant threat of nuclear warfare.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.helencaldicott.com/books/if-you-love-this-planet/|title=If You Love This Planet|website=Helen Caldicott, M.D.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref> A physician by training, Caldicott prescribes a cure and cause for hope. She suggests that individuals organize politically, learn energy efficiency, and hold corporations and governments accountable. She argues that love for the Earth itself should be the greatest strength in our fight for the planet.<ref name=\":1\" /> The film inspired Canadian Prime Minister [[Pierre Trudeau|Pierre Elliott Trudeau\u2019]]<nowiki/>s World Peace Tour to reduce nuclear arms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://povmagazine.com/articles/view/the-world-before-us|title=The World Before Us \u2013 Point of View Magazine|last=Toronto|first=Point of View Magazine \u2022 392-401 Richmond Street West \u2022|last2=email|first2=ON \u2022 M5V 3A8 \u2022 Canada \u2022639-0653 \u2022 Send us an|website=povmagazine.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref> The film was loved and reviewed by newspapers such as the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', ''[[East Bay Express]]'', and ''[[The Seattle Times]]''. The film also received praise from activist and filmmaker [[Naomi Klein]], and actress [[Meryl Streep]] has said that \u201cHelen Caldicott has been my inspiration to speak out.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Book==\nCaldicott later wrote a book of the same name, ''If You Love This Planet: A Plan to Heal the Earth'' (1992). A new edition of this book was published by [[W. W. Norton & Company]] in September 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/If-You-Love-This-Planet%3A-A-Plan-to-Heal-the-Earth-Caldicott/1f8a1fc04f5c9b4d37c1b46edb959d6854dd6f4f|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Radio Program==\nCaldicott hosted a weekly radio program called ''If You Love This Planet'' from July 2008 to November 2012.<ref>http://www.radio4all.net/index.php/program/65308</ref> The program was first aired by [[Pacifica Foundation]] station [[KPFT]] in [[Houston]], and played weekly on dozens of American., Canadian, and Australian radio stations. The series focused on the threats to human survival posed by nuclear weapons, [[nuclear power]], [[global warming]], [[pollution]], [[deforestation]], and other public health issues.\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Eight Minutes to Midnight: A Portrait of Dr. Helen Caldicott]]'', a 1981 feature-length documentary film\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0084118|title=If You Love This Planet}}\n*[http://www.nfb.ca/film/if_you_love_this_planet/ Watch ''If You Love this Planet'' at NFB.ca]\n*{{Amg movie|300477|If You Love This Planet}}\n*[http://ifyoulovethisplanet.org/ If You Love This Planet Radio Program]\n*[http://documentary.net/if-you-love-this-planet-1982-oscar-winning-film/ Full film at Documentary.net]\n\n{{AcademyAwardBestDocumentaryShort 1981\u20132000}}\n\n[[Category:1982 films]]\n[[Category:1982 in the environment]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:National Film Board of Canada documentaries]]\n[[Category:Best Documentary Short Subject Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about nuclear war and weapons]]\n[[Category:Canadian short documentary films]]\n[[Category:1980s documentary films]]\n[[Category:Anti\u2013nuclear weapons movement]]\n[[Category:Anti-nuclear films]]\n[[Category:Films about activists]]\n[[Category:National Film Board of Canada short films]]\n[[Category:Quebec films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = If You Love This Planet\n| image          = If You Love This Planet (film).jpg\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Terre Nash]]\n| producer       = [[Edward Le Lorrain]]\n| writer         =\n| narrator       =\n| starring       =\n| music          = [[Karl du Plessis]]\n| cinematography = [[Andr\u00e9-Luc Dupont]]<br />[[Susan Trow]]<br />[[Don Virgo]]\n| editing        =\n| distributor    = [[National Film Board of Canada]] (NFB)\n| released       = 1982\n| runtime        = 26 minutes\n| country        = Canada\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| preceded_by    =\n| followed_by    =\n}}\n'''''If You Love This Planet''''' is a 1982 short [[documentary film]] recording a lecture given to [[State University of New York at Plattsburgh|SUNY Plattsburgh]] students by physician and [[anti-nuclear]] activist Dr. [[Helen Caldicott]] about the dangers posed by [[nuclear weapon]]s.  The movie was directed by [[Terre Nash]] and produced by [[Edward Le Lorrain]] for [[National Film Board of Canada#Studio D|Studio D, the women's studio of the National Film Board of Canada]]. Studio D head [[Kathleen Shannon]] was executive producer.<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=Canada|first=National Film Board of|title=If You Love This Planet|url=https://www.nfb.ca/film/if_you_love_this_planet/|language=en|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref>\n\nReleased during the term of the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan administration]] and at the height<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.history.com/topics/cold-war/cold-war-history|title=Cold War History|last=Editors|first=History com|website=HISTORY|language=en|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref> of [[Cold War]] nuclear tensions between the United States and [[Soviet Union]], ''If You Love This Planet'' was officially designated as \"foreign political propaganda\" by the [[United States Department of Justice]] and temporarily banned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://explore.lib.virginia.edu/exhibits/show/censored/walkthrough/film2|title=CENSORED: Wielding the Red Pen (Online Exhibit)|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=23 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Verbinski|first=Jane|title=If You Love This Planet Gov't censors pick best short|journal=Jump Cut|date=April 1983|issue=28|page=64|url=http://www.ejumpcut.org/archive/onlinessays/JC28folder/CensorShort.html|accessdate=23 November 2013}}</ref>  The subsequent uproar over that action gave the film a [[Streisand Effect|publicity boost]], and it later won the 1982 [[Academy Award for Best Documentary (Short Subject)]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/300477/If-You-Love-This-Planet/details |title=If You Love This Planet |accessdate=2008-12-01|work=The New York Times}}</ref> [[CBC Television]] initially refused to air the film, claiming it was biased.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nelson|first=Joyce|date=1983|title=Film Reviews/Terri Nash's \"If You Love This Planet\"|url=http://cinemacanada.athabascau.ca/index.php/cinema/article/view/1715|journal=Cinema Canada|language=en|volume=0|issue=0|issn=1918-879X}}</ref> It debuted in the [[United Kingdom]] when it was screened by the London Socialist Film Co-op.<ref>Matthew Hays, [http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/1997/032097/film1.html \"Montreal Oscar Stories: Two of the city's award-winners reminisce\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020823090711/http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/1997/032097/film1.html |date=2002-08-23 }} ''Montreal Mirror'', March 21, 1997.  Accessed 2008.12.18.</ref>\n\n== Significance ==\nThe film goes into depth describing in easy-to-understand language the scientific and medical consequences of [[ozone depletion]], the [[greenhouse effect]], [[deforestation]], toxic chemical pollution, [[species extinction]], [[food contamination]], [[Nuclear Waste|nuclear waste]], and the constant threat of nuclear warfare.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.helencaldicott.com/books/if-you-love-this-planet/|title=If You Love This Planet|website=Helen Caldicott, M.D.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref> A physician by training, Caldicott prescribes a cure and cause for hope. She suggests that individuals organize politically, learn energy efficiency, and hold corporations and governments accountable. She argues that love for the Earth itself should be the greatest strength in our fight for the planet.<ref name=\":1\" /> The film inspired Canadian Prime Minister [[Pierre Trudeau|Pierre Elliott Trudeau\u2019]]<nowiki/>s World Peace Tour to reduce nuclear arms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://povmagazine.com/articles/view/the-world-before-us|title=The World Before Us \u2013 Point of View Magazine|last=Toronto|first=Point of View Magazine \u2022 392-401 Richmond Street West \u2022|last2=email|first2=ON \u2022 M5V 3A8 \u2022 Canada \u2022639-0653 \u2022 Send us an|website=povmagazine.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref> The film was loved and reviewed by newspapers such as the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', ''[[East Bay Express]]'', and ''[[The Seattle Times]]''. The film also received praise from activist and filmmaker [[Naomi Klein]], and actress [[Meryl Streep]] has said that \u201cHelen Caldicott has been my inspiration to speak out.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Book==\nCaldicott later wrote a book of the same name, ''If You Love This Planet: A Plan to Heal the Earth'' (1992). A new edition of this book was published by [[W. W. Norton & Company]] in September of 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/If-You-Love-This-Planet%3A-A-Plan-to-Heal-the-Earth-Caldicott/1f8a1fc04f5c9b4d37c1b46edb959d6854dd6f4f|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Radio Program==\nCaldicott hosted a weekly radio program called ''If You Love This Planet'' from July 2008 to November 2012.<ref>http://www.radio4all.net/index.php/program/65308</ref> The program was first aired by [[Pacifica Foundation]] station [[KPFT]] in [[Houston]], and played weekly on dozens of American., Canadian, and Australian radio stations. The series focused on the threats to human survival posed by nuclear weapons, [[nuclear power]], [[global warming]], [[pollution]], [[deforestation]], and other public health issues.\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Eight Minutes to Midnight: A Portrait of Dr. Helen Caldicott]]'', a 1981 feature-length documentary film\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0084118|title=If You Love This Planet}}\n*[http://www.nfb.ca/film/if_you_love_this_planet/ Watch ''If You Love this Planet'' at NFB.ca]\n*{{Amg movie|300477|If You Love This Planet}}\n*[http://ifyoulovethisplanet.org/ If You Love This Planet Radio Program]\n*[http://documentary.net/if-you-love-this-planet-1982-oscar-winning-film/ Full film at Documentary.net]\n\n{{AcademyAwardBestDocumentaryShort 1981\u20132000}}\n\n[[Category:1982 films]]\n[[Category:1982 in the environment]]\n[[Category:Canadian short films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:National Film Board of Canada documentaries]]\n[[Category:Best Documentary Short Subject Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about nuclear war and weapons]]\n[[Category:Canadian short documentary films]]\n[[Category:1980s documentary films]]\n[[Category:Anti\u2013nuclear weapons movement]]\n[[Category:Anti-nuclear films]]\n[[Category:Films about activists]]\n[[Category:National Film Board of Canada short films]]\n[[Category:Quebec films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "duplicate categorization; already in subcat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/If_You_Love_This_Planet"}
